<h6 class="kicker">Global History</h6>
<p class="summary">Teaching ideas based on New York Times content.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/category/global-history/">See all in Global History Â»</a></li>
<li><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/">See all lesson plans Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Overview | </strong>What is it about Russia and the Olympics? Back in 1980, some 65 nations including the United States <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/2013/1980olympicsboycottLN.pdf">boycotted the Summer Games in Moscow</a> (PDF) over the invasion of Afghanistan by the communist-led Soviet Union, as Russia was then known. Thirty-four years later, the athletes are returning â this time to the Black Sea resort of Sochi for the 22nd Winter Olympics â and so is the controversy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Three fatal bombings in the area have prompted tight security and a travel warning by the United States government. Gay rights activists &#8212; and some athletes &#8212; are planning to defy new Russian laws banning displays of what the authorities call âhomosexual propaganda.â Ordinary Russians continue to speak out about authoritarianism and crackdowns on dissent, while others say their president, Vladimir V. Putin, has saved the country from chaos. Relations with Western Europe and America are tense and mutually distrustful.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Against this backdrop, the Olympics will begin on Feb. 7. In this lesson we offer a range of stories and activities designed to help students think of this vast, multifaceted country, and some of the issues that will be in the spotlight when the Games begin. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-141446"></span></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Ways to Teach With This Content</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Below, 10 big questions students might consider in thinking about Russia and its readiness for the Sochi Olympics. Here are some ways you might teach with them:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Research and Present, in Groups or on Panels:</strong> Assign to small groups as many of the topics below as fit your curriculum or are of interest to your students. Have them research and then present their findings to the class ahead of the Olympics, which begin Feb. 7. Have each group create a brief presentation, or invite a representative from each group to be on a panel that discusses a question like, &#8220;How ready is Russia to host the Olympics?&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Create Visuals:</strong> As students research one or more of the topics below, invite them to show what they have learned by creating visuals of some kind, whether infographics like timelines that show how Russia has changed since 1980, or charts that relate key information about Mr. Putin. Or invite them to create slide shows of images that they narrate or annotate. The whole class could also contribute to a class or schoolwide Sochi Olympics gallery display. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Adopt a Topic and Follow It:</strong> Have students pick an issue, group or individual from the list below, do some reading and research for background and make predictions on what may happen next. Then track the issue, group or individual in The Times after the Olympics begin.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Host a Debate:</strong> Choose one of the questions below, divide students to research the arguments on each side, then organize a classroom debate. For instance: Was the mass boycott of the 1980 Olympics the right decision then, and should countries or participants consider a similar step now if they feel strongly about an issue? Invite students to research the issues in 1980 and <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/activities/DebatableIssues_NYTLN.pdf">develop a list of pros and cons,</a> then do the same for the 2014 Sochi Games, using some of the links below. Take class votes on both situations.</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Questions to Consider</strong></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/10/15/world/JP-RUSSIA-8-LN/JP-RUSSIA-8-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/10/15/world/JP-RUSSIA-8-LN/JP-RUSSIA-8-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/10/15/world/JP-RUSSIA-8-LN/JP-RUSSIA-8-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002649983" width="190" height="129" alt="A woman going to church at the lavishly renovated Iversky Monastery, outside Valdai, within sight of a vacation home used by President Vladimir V. Putin. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2013/10/13/russia/&quot;&gt;Go to related articleÂ Â»&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="129"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A woman going to church at the lavishly renovated Iversky Monastery, outside Valdai, within sight of a vacation home used by President Vladimir V. Putin. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2013/10/13/russia/">Go to related articleÂ Â»</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Dmitry Kostyukov for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How has Russia changed since the 1980 Olympics, and how are the Games changing Sochi?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under communist rule in the Soviet Union, citizens were provided basic needs such as food, housing and a job, but were forbidden from starting profit-making businesses. All of that has changed since the 1990s, when vast portions of the economy were converted to private ownership and ordinary citizens were left to fend for themselves. Todayâs Russia is a land of contrasts, with great wealth and modern conveniences in the major cities but deep poverty in rural areas. Join the Times reporter Ellen Barry on a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2013/10/13/russia/">train journey</a> she took last fall from St. Petersburg to Moscow to witness firsthand the growing inequality in small cities and villages. âGradually, everything is rotting,â one 52-year-old man said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Russia is also feeling economic strains because of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/21/world/europe/oil-wealth-reduced-russia-needs-to-lure-foreign-capital.html">overdependence on its vast oil wealth</a>, forcing the government to tap into <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/22/world/europe/russia-to-tap-reserve-funds-for-infrastructure-projects.html">reserve funds</a> to modernize the economy. Nowhere is this <a href="//www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/susan-ormiston-russia-s-50b-sochi-olympics-gamble-1.1409726">modernizing gamble</a> more apparent than the resort city of Sochi, where the government has been <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/02/07/world/europe/putins-vision-of-olympic-glory-meets-reality-in-sochi.html">rushing to build facilities</a> for the Winter Olympics. There is still plenty of evidence of the old Russia &#8212; an <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/20/sports/olympics/at-center-of-sochi-games-lies-a-cemetery.html">old cemetery</a> that has been preserved in Sochi, and the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/11/world/europe/at-chekhovs-estate-a-pastoral-literary-shrine-belies-a-turbulent-century.html">woodsy cottage</a> of the 19th century novelist Anton Chekhov.  But many people will tell you that the country has been <a href="//www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/how-russia-has-changed-since-its-last-olympic-games-1.1354046">transformed since the 1980 Olympics.</a></p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/31/world/31russia_web-LN/31russia_web-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/31/world/31russia_web-LN/31russia_web-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/31/world/31russia_web-LN/31russia_web-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002649653" width="190" height="127" alt="A bomb on a bus in Volgograd, Russia, on Dec. 30 killed at least 15 people. It was the second fatal blast in the city in two days. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/31/world/europe/russia-blasts-raise-olympic-fears.html&quot;&gt;Go to related articleÂ Â»&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A bomb on a bus in Volgograd, Russia, on Dec. 30 killed at least 15 people. It was the second fatal blast in the city in two days. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/31/world/europe/russia-blasts-raise-olympic-fears.html">Go to related articleÂ Â»</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Is Sochi a risky place to hold the Olympics?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Russia has <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/multimedia/100000002637925/russia-tightens-security-in-sochi-before-olympics.html">tightened security</a> in Sochi following a series of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/31/world/europe/russia-blasts-raise-olympic-fears.html">suicide bombings</a> in the city of Volgograd, which is about 600 miles away, and the United States State Department responded by issuing a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/11/sports/olympics/americans-traveling-to-winter-games-cautioned.html">travel warning</a>. It was not the first sign of trouble in the Caucasus Mountains region, which for centuries has been troubled by separatist movements and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/06/opinion/winter-games-caucasian-misery.html">violent conflict</a> with the government. Even the United States-educated men accused of last springâs Boston Marathon bombing were said to be <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/world/europe/boston-attacks-turn-spotlight-on-troubled-chechen-region.html">inspired</a> by rebels in the Russian republics of Dagestan and Chechnya, with one of the Tsarnaev brothers <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/05/09/world/europe/boston-bombing-inquiry-looks-closely-at-russia-trip.html">traveling</a> to the region in 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So are Olympic athletes and visitors in danger? Experts on the Russian security services say it is possible the Games can be safely <a href="//www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/europe/russia/140110/will-anyone-attack-the-sochi-winter-olympics-5-questions-">cordoned off</a> by moving vast numbers of forces into the Sochi region, but doing so could leave other parts of Russia <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-01-12/putin-sochi-ski-cameo-fails-to-ease-olympic-terror-fears.html">more vulnerable</a> to attacks.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/02/sports/olympics/02sochi-LN/02sochi-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/02/sports/olympics/02sochi-LN/02sochi-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/02/sports/olympics/02sochi-LN/02sochi-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002649647" width="190" height="137" alt="Gay-rights activists protested in front of the Russian consulate in New York in July 2013. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/02/sports/olympics/new-russian-law-stirs-olympic-controversy.html&quot;&gt;Go to related articleÂ Â»&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="137"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Gay-rights activists protested in front of the Russian consulate in New York in July 2013. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/02/sports/olympics/new-russian-law-stirs-olympic-controversy.html">Go to related articleÂ Â»</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mary Altaffer/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why are gay rights such an issue in Russia?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The issue of gay rights emerged in 2012 after Parliament <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/03/01/world/asia/anti-gay-law-stirs-fears-in-russia.html">passed a law</a> restricting âhomosexual propaganda.â Last summer Russiaâs minister of sports, Vitaly L. Mutko, fanned the controversy by <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/02/sports/olympics/new-russian-law-stirs-olympic-controversy.html">asserting</a> that visiting Olympic athletes could be arrested for advocating a ânontraditionalâ sexual orientation. David M. Herszenhorn, a Times foreign correspondent, reported that, legal or not, gay people in Russia face <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/12/world/europe/gays-in-russia-find-no-haven-despite-support-from-the-west.html">widespread discrimination</a> and even violent attacks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While Mr. Putin has insisted that gay athletes and guests are <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/10/29/world/europe/russia-putin-says-sochi-welcomes-gays.html">welcome</a> in Sochi, many gay athletes and their supporters say they plan to be upfront about sexuality at the Winter Olympics. President Obama protested the situation by naming an official delegation to the Games that includes <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/18/sports/olympics/obama-names-gay-athletes-to-delegation.html">openly gay athletes</a> but no high-level officials, and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/07/sports/olympics/impromptu-coming-out-for-olympic-star.html">athletes</a> from several countries say they <a href="//www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/nov/20/winter-olympics-sochi-gay-blake-skjellerup">will not hide</a> their orientation in Sochi.</p>
