<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Hasnât Russiaâs president been letting people out of jail and allowing more protest recently?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There has been an apparent thaw in the weeks leading up to the Winter Olympics, with Mr. Putin releasing imprisoned members of the rock group <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/24/world/europe/member-of-russian-punk-band-freed-under-amnesty-law.html">Pussy Riot</a>, a group of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/25/world/europe/russian-amnesty-now-includes-greenpeace-case.html">Greenpeace protesters</a> and a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/23/opinion/insights-into-democracy-refined-in-a-russian-prison.html">billionaire</a> who had opposed him politically. He even <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/05/world/europe/putin-loosens-ban-on-protests-in-sochi.html">eased a ban</a> on protesting during the Olympics. But critics say these acts are little more than a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/22/world/europe/with-punishments-or-pardons-putin-shows-he-is-in-control.html">public relations ploy</a> and demonstrate the extent of his power. âWhat we are seeing is a president who has no limits on his power in a country that never was democratic, that never had anything called a balance of power,â the Russian journalist Vladimir Posner said.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/22/world/PUTIN-LN/PUTIN-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/22/world/PUTIN-LN/PUTIN-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/12/22/world/PUTIN-LN/PUTIN-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002650034" width="190" height="122" alt="President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia is keeping his foes off balance with actions like the pardon on Dec. 20, 2013, of the tycoon Mikhail B. Khodorkovsky. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/22/world/europe/with-punishments-or-pardons-putin-shows-he-is-in-control.html&quot;&gt;Go to related articleÂ Â»&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="122"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia is keeping his foes off balance with actions like the pardon on Dec. 20, 2013, of the tycoon Mikhail B. Khodorkovsky. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/22/world/europe/with-punishments-or-pardons-putin-shows-he-is-in-control.html">Go to related articleÂ Â»</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Vasily Maximov/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Who is Vladimir Putin, and how did he become so powerful?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2000/01/10/world/putin-was-once-decorated-as-a-spy-few-agree-on-his-deeds.html">Trained as a K.G.B. spy</a> during the Cold War, Vladimir V. Putin was a political unknown until the 1990s, when he served as a city councilman and deputy major in St. Petersburg and was eventually appointed head of Russiaâs new security service.  A year later he was appointed prime minister and began calling for <a href="//www.nytimes.com/1999/11/14/opinion/why-we-must-act.html">firm action</a> in the war in Chechnya, setting the stage for a dramatic rise to power in 2000 with the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2000/01/01/world/yeltsin-resigns-overview-yeltsin-resigns-naming-putin-acting-president-run-march.html">surprise resignation</a> of Boris N. Yeltsin as president.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Read about Mr. Putinâs life and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2000/02/20/world/path-power-political-profile-putin-steering-reform-but-with-soviet-discipline.html">early career</a> in this <a href="//www.cbc.ca/news2/interactives/putin-timeline/">interactive timeline</a>, and consider the ways in which he gradually <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2000/06/01/world/putin-s-plan-to-centralize-power-in-the-kremlin-wins-a-round.html">centralized power</a> after being <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2000/05/08/world/putin-is-made-russia-s-president-in-first-free-transfer-of-power.html">elected</a> to his first full term as president. Then consider some of his actions to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2007/12/01/arts/01abroad.html">reform Russian culture</a>, establish his reputation among voters as a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2008/10/08/world/europe/08putin.html">masculine leader</a>, and restore a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/03/17/world/europe/cossacks-are-back-in-russia-may-the-hills-tremble.html">sense of pride</a> for a national history in which <a href="//www.nytimes.com/slideshow/2013/03/16/world/europe/20130317-COSSACK.html">fierce Cossacks</a> secured the national borders. What factors do you think most account for his continuing popularity among many Russian voters?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Has Russia become more or less democratic under Mr. Putin?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Vladimir Putin has been focusing on the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2000/03/26/world/russians-vote-under-the-spell-of-putin-s-many-promises.html">need for security</a> and order since the beginning of his political career, and he has gradually expanded this message to include other themes like <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2007/11/29/world/europe/29russiaweb.html">patriotism and economic recovery</a>. But some critics, including former <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/02/world/europe/gorbachev-attacks-putin-and-his-restrictions.html">President Mikhail S. Gorbachev</a>, charge that his rise has come at the cost of the sorts of democratic freedoms that Russians wanted in the waning years of the Cold War.  Mr. Putin has <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/world/europe/vladimir-putin-defends-decision-to-seek-russian-presidency.html">vigorously defended</a> those choices. But others like the former Canadian ambassador Jeremy Kinsman say he has abandoned the âmodest, self-effacingâ demeanor of his early career and <a href="//www.cbc.ca/news/world/jeremy-kinsman-russia-s-vladimir-putin-democrat-or-dictator-1.1345155">ignored good opportunities</a> to build democracy. Do you think President Putin has taken Russia in the right direction?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Is Russia a place where people can protest freely and write what they want?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In recent years, some Russians say they have begun to feel more hopeless and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/01/06/world/europe/in-russia-a-trendy-activism-against-putin-loses-its-moment.html">less interested in protesting</a> compared to the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/12/11/world/europe/thousands-protest-in-moscow-russia-in-defiance-of-putin.html">past</a>. But others, like the blogger Aleksei Navalny, have persisted. He was <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/07/19/world/europe/Navalny_timeline_quotes.html">bugged, jailed, tried and convicted</a> on charges of embezzlement, which he says were trumped up, and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/07/world/europe/for-kremlin-critic-out-of-jail-and-into-politics.html">promptly returned</a> to his political campaigning against Mr. Putin upon his release pending appeal.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What is clear is that protesting can lead to <a href="//latitude.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/12/masha-gessen-in-russia-the-sense-of-free-space-in-closing-in/">violent clashes</a> with the police. And for some journalists such as Anna Politkovskaya, who was murdered in 2006, challenging the government <a href="//latitude.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/10/08/masha-gessen-remembering-anna-politkovskaya/?nl=todaysheadlines&#038;emc=edit_ee_20121009">can be fatal</a>.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/06/19/world/DIPLO-LN/DIPLO-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/06/19/world/DIPLO-LN/DIPLO-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/06/19/world/DIPLO-LN/DIPLO-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002650001" width="190" height="107" alt="President Obama had a chilly meeting with President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia in June 2013.Â  &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/world/americas/extending-a-hand-abroad-obama-often-finds-a-cold-shoulder.html&quot;&gt;Go to related articleÂ Â»&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="107"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">President Obama had a chilly meeting with President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia in June 2013.Â  <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/world/americas/extending-a-hand-abroad-obama-often-finds-a-cold-shoulder.html">Go to related articleÂ Â»</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Kevin Lamarque/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why have the United States and Russia gotten into conflict lately, and can anything be done to improve the situation?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In recent years the United States and Russia have sparred over a range of issues, from Americaâs plans for <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/11/24/world/europe/russia-elevates-warning-about-us-missile-defense-shield-plan.html">missile defense</a> in Europe to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/09/19/world/europe/russia-demands-us-end-pro-democracy-work.html">democracy-building efforts</a> and the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/05/17/world/middleeast/russia-provides-syria-with-advanced-missiles.html">war in Syria</a>. Some of the disagreements have a particular Cold War flavor. In 2010 the United States expelled 11 people it suspected of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2010/06/29/world/europe/29spy.html">spying for Russia on America</a> from its suburbs, and last spring Russian agents in Moscow arrested a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/05/15/world/europe/russia-detains-american-saying-he-is-cia-agent.html">United States diplomat allegedly wearing a blond wig</a> whom they accused of similar acts. More recently, the former National Security Agency analyst <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/29/world/europe/while-nsa-leaker-stays-in-hiding-russian-tv-builds-a-pedestal-for-him.html">Edward J. Snowden</a> landed in Russia after releasing classified United States intelligence and was celebrated on national television there.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Experts disagree on whether President Obama and Mr. Putin can work together. Recent meetings suggest they have a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/world/americas/extending-a-hand-abroad-obama-often-finds-a-cold-shoulder.html">poor relationship</a> and little common ground, and some analysts say they believe that <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/06/opinion/global/the-kremlins-world.html">conflict is inevitable</a>. But others say the United States and Russia have a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/09/01/opinion/the-us-should-still-talk-to-russia.html">range of vital interests</a> and should not fall into the Cold War pattern of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/08/22/opinion/global/the-drive-to-blame-russia.html">demonizing each other</a>, or that there are <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/01/25/opinion/dealing-with-two-russias.html">essentially two Russias</a> and America can potentially find common ground in some areas. What do you think? Should countries keep talking and seeking areas of agreement, even when their relationship hits rock bottom?</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/10/30/business/30chocolate-span-LN/30chocolate-span-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/10/30/business/30chocolate-span-LN/30chocolate-span-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/10/30/business/30chocolate-span-LN/30chocolate-span-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002650085" width="190" height="127" alt="Inspecting chocolate-covered hazelnuts at the Roshen factory in Kiev, Ukraine. The sweets are banned in Russia. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/business/international/ukrainian-chocolates-caught-in-trade-war-between-europe-and-russia.html&quot;&gt;Go to related articleÂ Â»&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Inspecting chocolate-covered hazelnuts at the Roshen factory in Kiev, Ukraine. The sweets are banned in Russia. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/business/international/ukrainian-chocolates-caught-in-trade-war-between-europe-and-russia.html">Go to related articleÂ Â»</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Joseph Sywenkyj for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Is Russia getting along any better with its European neighbors?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bitter competition has been the name of the game in recent years as Russia and the European Union have vied for lucrative trade agreements and influence in countries that made up republics of the former Soviet Union. In Ukraine, Russia cut off a famed <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/business/international/ukrainian-chocolates-caught-in-trade-war-between-europe-and-russia.html">chocolate maker</a> amid <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/10/world/europe/ukraine-unrest.html">violent protests</a> as the country threatened to work with the European Union, and ultimately <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/18/world/europe/russia-offers-ukraine-financial-lifeline.html">rewarded it</a> with at least $15 billion in aid and trade incentives for swinging its way. Other countries, from <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/17/business/global/potash-dispute-heightens-tension-between-russia-and-belarus.html">Belarus</a> to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/11/17/world/europe/putin-parries-merkels-jabs-on-rights.html">Germany</a>, have faced their own conflicts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Is it O.K. for outside countries or individuals to criticize Russiaâs human rights record? And would a boycott or protests during the Olympics make matters better or worse?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whether foreign countries should interfere in each otherâs domestic politics â even when human rights are at stake â is an open debate in world forums like the United Nations. In this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2012/09/24/should-the-us-be-a-political-player-in-russia">Room for Debate feature</a>, a range of experts weigh in on the question of whether the United States should try to influence politics in Russia. On the question of an Olympics protest or boycott, too, opinion is divided. Some commentators say the Olympics should be <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/19/sports/olympics/olympics-invite-trouble-when-politics-drive-choices.html">about sports, not politics</a>. Others say Americaâs decision to boycott the 1980 Moscow Olympics did nothing more than <a href="//bruni.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/29/an-olympic-legend-on-boycotts-and-bigotry/">ruin years of preparation</a> for sports glory and set off a chain of retaliatory moves, with the Soviet Union and its allies skipping the 1984 Los Angeles Summer Olympics. But members of Pussy Riot who were jailed for protesting Mr. Putin say human rights are more important, and they are <a href="//www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-25496255">urging a boycott of the Sochi Games</a>. Do you think a boycott is warranted? Can international sports events like the Olympics ever be disentangled from politics, and should foreign countries feel free to criticize each other over human rights?</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>GOING FURTHER</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Boycotts in Olympics History:</strong> In 1980 the United States boycotted the Olympic Games in Moscow in response to the Soviet Unionâs invasion of Afghanistan. But Moscow wasnât the first time the <a href="//bruni.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/07/29/an-olympic-legend-on-boycotts-and-bigotry/">question of a boycott</a> came up. Many people had argued for boycotting the 1936 Berlin Games, which have been described as a propaganda triumph for Hitlerâs Nazi government. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ask students to brainstorm a list of conditions under which boycotting an Olympics might be appropriate. As a class, watch <a href="https://ushmm.org/museum/exhibit/online/olympics/videos/">this video on the 1936 Olympics</a> from the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum. Then read these stories on the <a href="//www.ushmm.org/exhibition/olympics/">âNazi Olympicsâ</a> and the Carter administrationâs decision to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/1996/07/19/sports/olympics-bitterness-lingering-over-carter-s-boycott.html">boycott the 1980 Moscow Games</a>. Divide students into six groups: athletes, 1936; the United States Olympic Committee, 1936; the White House, 1936; athletes, 1980; the United States Olympic Committee, 1980; and the White House, 1980. Ask each group to use the boycott criteria established by the class to reconsider the original decision, vote as a group and report back to the class on their deliberations. Then hold two classwide votes on whether to overturn Americaâs original decisions from 1936 and 1980.</p>
<hr/>
